Slowing down on content for a while. I need time to get back into a new rhythm of work and life. I’ll still be posting, just a little less for a month or two while I get adjusted and recharge from some really fast-paced months.

A merry solstice to you all ❄️ 

Stay warm, as I know many of you are getting this freezing storm rolling in as well as us here in Colorado. 

Swipe for an older piece of art of mine, something that reminds me of scrying on the darkest day of the year.

I personally feel like the winter solstice is the true marker of a new year. 

The longest night of the year to be met with the sun staying longer in the sky each day. The energy of the Death card is prominent. Having the snow fall and this freeze blanketed everything in silence. 

I’ve just posted a short video on YouTube, giving a peek into what is to come on my channel in the new year. Happy holidays to you all, and I wish you a wonderful New Year.

A Merry Christmas Eve to you! 

Personally I celebrate Christmas Eve more than the actual day, but it’s just family tradition for me we’d always open presents after it got dark, and my dad woke up right before he headed off to work the graveyard shift. We’d spend all day watching Christmas movies the next day, while I remember loving to sit and tinker and build whatever my parents decided to buy me that year hyped up on hot chocolate. 

Now, celebration usually takes over the whole month rather than waiting for one day, as I help my mom make budbud(suman), I get excited for the snow fall and indulge in all the festive food and drink, my friends and I go to the Denver Zoo Lights, and our friend Herman does his best to make us all cry in front of everyone with his stupid thoughtful gifts. 

My personal traditions for the winter solstice and Yule include wondering through the silent cemeteries  blanketed in snow, doing less spell work and more divination and planning, restring and refreshing my bigger protections, and interestingly enough, it’s the one time of year I do the most scrying in my black mirror. 

What do you celebrate? What kind of traditions do you have?
What a year. Probably one of my best yet.

I think we romanticize people who love to read, because that’s an indicator of someone who is inquisitive, thoughtful and has depth. 

We like the idea of someone wanting to turn our pages, be patient and curious enough to sit down to know our story too, approaching us with empathy. We like the idea of someone who sees the world in a poetic way, who can understand and put into words feelings and experiences we aren’t sure if others have ever known.
They’re seen as raw and unapologetic, and I think that’s what many of us crave to be. 

Or maybe it’s just the aesthetic. Just some afternoon thoughts.

Meet the “black magic” or the Colocasia esculenta, a variation that turns a purple so deep it’s almost black, and the maroon stem breaks into crawling veins on the grey underside of the leaf. 
I’ve never seen them growing outside a nursery, so you can imagine my excitement when I spotted so many in bunches here in Costa Rica. 

I post any photography I take on trips for my patrons in a format usable for wallpaper on phones and desktops. I tend to love “dark botanical” shots.

I’m editing together some cool shots & a vlog of my recent trip to Costa Rica all with a huge giveaway for a trip I was gifted to give to one of you. All the details will be coming in the next few weeks, but first I’ll need some time to edit it all together. 

In the mean time, thank you to @landsinlove and @animalloverescue for the wonderful opportunity and amazing work you all do with animal rescue. 

A thanks to @sunny16shop for my much needed waterproof camera bag during the excursions and rainy evenings.

And thank you to Costa Rica for having me!

When I was a kid I told my parents I wanted to be a traveling photographer who worked for National Geographic, because I wanted to travel and learn things by being immersed in the world, documenting it all along the way. 

Then, about 6 years ago I wanted to be a full time youtuber. I just wanted something I could do that was creative, pushed me out of my comfort zones, taught me things and that made some kind of positive impact on people. 

I had teachers in school tell me it was a pipe dream. I had friends and family tell me to have a “back up plan,” and honestly I’m not stranger to feeling like the underdog and ugly duckling. It’s not as cool as the movies make it seem unfortunately. 

I’m constantly always shocked and grateful for the opportunities my job gives me. I meet awesome people, I get to constantly be creative, learn new things, travel and document it all. 

8 year old Olivia would be so excited that we did it. I really hope the same happens for you, and that one day you look back and realize you have exactly what you use to wish for, and that often people don’t believe in you until you’re already successful.

Hello from the forest of these colocasias 👋🏼 

My partner recently said to me, “you have way too many thoughts for one head.”

It’s funny because I often get comments when people get to know me about how “intense” I can be. I’m always so incredibly interested when I hear people’s assumptions or perspectives of me and how they change as we spend more time together, as they go from thinking I totally have my shit together to seeing the reality of my (slightly) obsessive personality and neurotic tendencies to keep myself sane in organizing my white noise of constant thoughts.

I have what I call my “neurotic journal.” It’s a journal that travels everywhere with me, and gets anything and everything thrown into it. Thoughts, ideas, quotes, reminders, lists, references, doodles, poetry - all of it. I’m more uncomfortable without my journal than I am without my phone. 

If I put it on paper it can leave my head and I get a sense of peace for the time being. 

That’s just one of my many systems I’ve created for myself to keep myself organized, and for lack of better words, sane. 

Do you have any systems or tactics you’ve created for your own sense of peace or sanity?

Something I’ve always struggled with, is balancing my soft/dark and feminine/masculine energies. 

I think it’s something we all struggle with. But for me, I grew up being comfortable in my masculine energy. Anything feminine felt like it wasn’t made for me. As I became more comfortable in feminine energy, I realized the the dark energy was where I felt most comfortable to exist - for better of for worse. 

While I can go back and forth of my softer and darker energies, the specific place I’ve had the most trouble with is learning to comfortably exist in soft energy for long periods of time. Even a whole day is a struggle for me if I’m not remaining focused. 

Too much dark fem&masc energy has manifested in ways like my boundaries being so intense that people struggle to create even a foundation of a relationship with me, I sometimes come off as cold and indifferent, and my lust for solitude can be crippling to many aspects of my life. 

I hope to create more space for softer energy, to become more comfortable with the warm and inviting, and I crave the gentleness I could have when so often I feel like a storm. 

Balance is everything, as I’ve believed my whole life; but balance is a life long lesson. 

The goal is to be comfortably liminal.

I’m learning a lot of new things right now. 

I love learning something new - I always gain new perspectives, new understandings, a new skill and I’m always humbled by how much I don’t know.

It’s daunting, but I’m glad I have some horticulture experience and contacts to help me along. I plan to document it all along the way for both myself and anyone who’s interested.

I’m struggling a lot with imposter syndrome with my content, and finding I am absolutely not as healed as I thought with a lot of my traumas. 

A friend recently told me, that healthy situations can bring to light the unhealed parts of us and let me tell you, I am experiencing that to an all time high.

I’m grateful that I can see these things, but I still feel like shit about it. My reactions and expectations are a lot less healthy than I originally thought they were. My brain doesn’t compute with stability, basically. Now that I live in a home that I don’t rent, in a relationship that feels stable, I am living every waking moment in waiting for the complete downfall of it all. I can’t bring myself to settle in and get comfortable because I don’t believe anything good lasts. And I want that to change so badly. 

I didn’t realize how bad my trust issues were until recently, and holy shit it sucks. 

Content wise, I always feel like a liar. I know that I keep things from the public eye, but I want to feel safe while also feeling like I’m in touch with my community and audience. It’s such a difficult thing to navigate and not anything anyone can help you learn. 

I always tell people, I’m much cooler on the internet. I think if you look at my content at a glance, sure, I look like I have my shit together. But I hope that the closer you look, you’ll see me for what I am: an introverted nerd, who longs for community but is still working through those internal issues to fully attain it. Just being one of the many ways to be human, the best I can. 

So… just gonna hit post and send this one into the void now.

Things I would tell myself as a beginner practitioner:

1. You know more than you’re giving yourself credit for. Relearn to trust yourself. 
2. Fuck around and find out. Experimentation will teach you more than reading any book, watching any video, or going to any lecture will.
3. If it makes you enjoy life more, that’s all that matters. 
4. Magic and the mundane are not separate, so don’t treat them as such.
5. Even if it doesn’t make sense right now, it will. 
6. Practice when you need to, and when you want to. This is your lifestyle and belief, not a productivity list. 
7. What happens between you and spirits, stay between you and spirits. 
8. Even the healers need healing. 
9. The more you learn, the less you’ll realize you actually know. 
10. Being a practitioner is inherently political.

“I sent you omens and all kinds of signs… I taught you melodies, poems and rhymes…”

Something about this song makes me feel like it’s a shaman trying to desperately explain the things they see and hear and know, how it’s at our fingertips and right in front of our eyes, but as I’m sure many of you know, it’s not something you can explain to someone to understand. The shaman, on their death bed, tries to teach the young ones what they learned from the spirits, with the sacred songs, the poems, the stories and rhymes to pass down to their next generation, keeping that thread of contact with the gods of old and ancestors of the names they no longer know but still gather around when called. 

It feels as if the shaman stands on one side of a oneway mirror, clearly seeing, while others look to the other side of the mirror, saying “it’s just glass.”

What no one tells you, is once you get this “sight,” you are very much alone in what you see.

What is going to improve your practice and connection the most? 

Doing it. 

So simple, yet I see so many of us, including myself, get all the info, read all the books, watch all the videos and get all the tools, but then find ourselves paralyzed when the time to actually do the thing is presented. The overthinking begins. 

Don’t know how to interact with the spirits in the cemetery? Go there and learn. Don’t know what offerings to give to the river spirits? Try offering something and they’ll tell you if it’s fit or not. Not sure if your candle is working? Await results, and then try again, adjust accordingly. Try something slightly different this time. Can’t tell if your tree spirits in the back yard like you? Use your cards or sit with them for a bit and find out. Does that spirit from the bones you have care to work with you? Ask. Does burning cedar clear those pesky entities as well as juniper? Light em up and find out. 

Go stumble. Go make mistakes. 

There is no verification anyone can give you. Everything in the beginning will feel clunky and awkward. You’ll feel lost and unsure. But if you wait to be fully confident before you dive in, you never will. You’re a witch, after all. 

So what’s stopping you?

READ if you are thinking of visiting:

This amazing structure is hand built by a man named Jim Bishop. Incredible to see, beautiful views and has a very whimsical style to it, with the curly Qs woven into the metal, huge cathedral-style windows and dragon on the forefront. It’s a free and unique attraction in Rye, CO, about 3 hours from Denver. 

If you plan to visit, keep these things in mind:
1. It is an enter at your own risk attraction. There are many places in this structure that with one wrong step, you can easily slip a foot into a hole and have a terrible accident, or fall from the towering heights. 
2. If you are afraid of heights, might not be the place for you. Most of the attraction is climbing the winding staircases with missing railings and unstable stairs in low lighting. 
3. It is not accessible to those who have difficulty or are unable to walk. There are no elevators and no paved pathways. 

Have you been here? Would you scale the towering metal structures and along the sides of the building?

One of the biggest parts of my practice is something more subtle that makes a huge difference, and it doesn’t include large rituals or even tools, spells or charms, really. 

Do you ever wake up on a Wednesday and think, “it feels like a Sunday”? For some reason the energy of the day seems laid back and easy going, instead of the struggle to get through the rest of the week. Or maybe something just felt heavy in the air all day, with no explanation. 

Whatever the day feels like, I’ll lean into it. If I’m teaching pole, I’ll fill that energy into the room before starting. Maybe it’s a high impact day - or maybe it’s a “Sunday” feeling day that needs some easygoing grooves and light hearted freestyles instead. 

I’ll wear something that feels fitting for that energy, listen to fitting music, or try to fit in an activity that goes best with the current days energy. Could be journaling and taking a walk for those heavy or uneasy days, or maybe it’s getting the adulting tasks done for the high energy or productive feeling days.

Basically, don’t question the energy of the day, just go with it. If you have trouble sensing the energy, try using the planetary placements or draw a tarot card to help you get a better understanding. 

A lot of my practice isn’t something i can film and share, it’s things I actively and subtly do as a magical and liminal being.

The people you love are going to die. 

The moment you’re in right now, you will never get back. 

A routine, “see you soon!” Could be the last time you see them. 

If you lost everything and everyone you loved, but then got one chance to have it all back again, how would you live your life, knowing the timer is always ticking, but you can’t see the clock?

I don’t say this to cause anxiety or fear, but to remind us that everything dies. Moments, relationships, feelings, people - everything is temporary. Remember this next time you’re in a rut, have a shitty day or something terrible happens. It will end. Remember this for the good things too, the people you love and the feelings you feel. Relish in those. Say how you feel, love hard, be intense, wear that outfit, try that new thing.

This is a whole topic, but here are my biggest pointers when beginning to work with graveyard spirits:

1. Visit your local cemeteries. Each one will have a different feel and different spirits. They are all their own individual entities, so treat them as such. Some may not like you, and that’s okay. Respect that. Once you find a cemetery you feel connected to, visit often. Check the cemeteries website or office for the rules, as each one is different. 

2. Wear a head covering or some kind of protective amulet or oil, especially the first few times you visit a new cemetery.  Better safe than sorry. If you feel icky in anyway after visiting, be sure to cleanse before you get back home. 

3. Don’t try asking the spirits for help without a massive payment upfront. If a stranger asked you for a favor in exchange for a dollar, you’d probably say no. So build a relationship first and get to know the spirits in the cemetery you frequent without expecting or asking for anything in return for a while. 

4. Divination is your friend. While building a relationship, spirits often LOVE just chatting. They don’t get visitors often that give them access to speak as well. I have some spirits that love the daily gossip, while others want to give unsolicited advice. Remember, they’re just people. Treat them as such. 

5. Offerings. Don’t over think this, either. This can be cleaning up the trash you find, coins, some tea you brewed and pour out, a flower or fruit from your garden, or if you are good at energy work and don’t mind giving that during a small meditation. Most of the time this will be at the gates, and maybe near the headstones of those you choose to commune with. 

6. When you do ask for a spirits help, ask them for permission first. If you’re not getting a “NO” feeling, it’s probably fine. This may be setting your spellwork at their headstone(make sure it’s safe for both the environment, won’t be litter, and safe for other living visitors), or using a small amount of the dirt in your workings. Payment before or after the spellwork will depend on the spirit, the spell and you relationship.

There’s something about the way the air feels and smells in the autumn, something sweet and nostalgic. Something that connects me in a way I don’t know how to explain. 

Enjoy your cozy nights and chilly mornings. Enjoy the creaky coffee and pumpkin-spiced-everything. Enjoy smell of books and the cinnamon sticks. Enjoy the muted tones and cozy sweaters, the autumn boots and the sound of crunchy leaves underneath them. Enjoy it all, because we only have a short time in til Death decides autumn’s time is up. TIPS FOR LIVING LIKE A WITCH

☕️ Weave your practice into the life you already live. 

Showers, baths, tea, cooking, makeup, hobbies like knitting or painting, gardening and even just adding charms in your pockets, shoes, or in the car or sigils on your metro pass. Living like a witch is rarely as movie-magical as we hope. It’s in the subtleties of the everyday. 

☕️ Work with magic that feels familiar to you. 

Don’t force yourself into a practice that doesn’t feel familiar. If you gravitate naturally to cooking magic, don’t put that on the back burner while you force yourself to work with planetary magic when it feels too foreign. Obviously you should learn and grow in your practice, but if it doesn’t inspire you, spark your curiosity or make you excited, the effects may be hindered. 

☕️ Focus on magic that enriches your life. 
The way people use their practice is different for everyone. How do you want YOUR life to be enriched? Strengthening community? Glamours to help you in the work setting during presentations? A magical and protected home to have a little sanctuary for you and loved ones? 

☕️ Comparison helps no one. 
If you couldn’t gather from the other tips, everyone’s practice is different. That’s the beauty of it. To compare your craft to someone else’s, how “powerful” they are or how aesthetic their spells and rituals are - will help no one. The reality of a practice is one that follows the tips above. Some may be more flashy or more power punched, but our crafts are like ourselves, and the differences are what make our crafts strong and meaningful.

Altars in general have a special place in my heart, but working altars specifically are my favorite. Working altars are the spaces practitioners do most of their work, not specific to any spirits or deities usually. They can be set up in any way, they can be temporary or permanent. They can be minimal or a mess of charmed items and incense ash. They are personal to the practice and practitioner. A liminal space to work. 

There is something about a working altar that radiates comfort, warmth and wisdom. I was taught to never let an altar go cold, whether that means offerings, a continuous working, or some kind of meditation or divination in its space. Always movement in energies, never allowing the energy of the altar to go stale or still, keeping away that “energetic dust.”

Working your main altar like this imbues the space and the items on your alter with energy, it’s like a hotspot that keeps charging. The set up of these altars for me have evolved dramatically over the years, consistently moving things and switching things out to make the energy flow the best it can. 

What questions do you have about working altars?

I’ve been a creator for a long time now.

Realistically, it’s my income, so I can’t just… stop. 

I miss creating because it meant something to me. I miss dancing because it embodied emotion. I miss documenting. I miss the documentation through photography, sketchbooks and little captions like this. I miss going back through my feed and thinking “oh wow! I remember that!” And the vivid feelings it takes me back to. 

I feel desaturated. Uninspired. Bored. I feel like a trapped bird wasting away in a cage. 

The death of inspiration is the death of the artist.

I’ve been trying to figure out what that exactly means. I know what that *feels* like, but I’ve been struggling to put it into words. While I know the witchy side isn’t leaving, since it’s a huge part of my life, I think it’s going to be more integrated into the vlogs as just my every day. I don’t think I could ever live somewhere without snow. 

The snow just means too much to me. When it blankets the world it hushes it all, muting the busyness and bustle, everyone seems restful and sleepy, cozied up inside. I love the long nights, allowing me to exist in this liminal space the cold creates. Laying in the snow while it falls with nothing but a full moon illuminating the sky. The chill of outside reminds me of the brutality life brings, but I’m always fortunate enough to have a warm place to rest. 

The spirit of winter brings me peace. It brings me rest. I find comfort in the reset of things. Maybe it because it reminds me of Death.

I took this photo in Denver back in… 2017, maybe? It was a long time ago. I had it as my wallpaper for the longest time, and I remember looking at it all the time and aching to go back to Denver, as I was living in LA at the time. 

I visited often while I lived away, and every time I did, Colorado felt less and less familiar but the time I moved back, Denver now feels like a budding LA. Everyone wants to live here, housing is being built cheaply and rented out expensively. So many of the back roads my friends and I used to drive around on with nothing but fields in view are covered in strip malls and cookie cutter apartment buildings and suburbs. 

I’m glad people like it here, but I’m sad to see so much of the small town vibe be steamrolled by industry and capitalism. I’m sad to see my favorite hiking spots get trashed and graffitied. 

It’s funny to me, because growing up when I told people I was from CO they’d always kinda shrug and say okay. But now, I get the reaction of “wow🤩 Colorado?! I LOVE it there I want to live there SO badly!!!”

It’s just funny to watch time move. To watch things change and evolve and turn into something new. Especially something like your hometown, that you thought would always be stuck in time.

I was having a conversation with someone recently about how I’m not able to really express my feelings and thoughts into words immediately for the most part unless given an ample amount of time to process and structure the things I want to say with the specific words I want to choose as to try my best not to be misunderstood. 

I said that’s why I’m a visual creator; because I have an easier time expressing an emotion or concept through something I can show instead of tell. I feel the best way to have someone truly understand what I’m thinking or feeling is by setting up a mood, an aesthetic, a photo or video with the specific mood and intention I want to get across. 

I liked this brief conversation because it gave me a new perspective on how people operate and process differently than I do. I always want to pick apart people’s processes and look inside to see how they work. How do you process things easiest?

2024 has been very good to me so far. I hope it’s been good to you too. 

It’s been a while since I’ve said hi, since there’s actually been a lot of new people to this page(and my bookstagram) since the last time I’ve introduced myself. So, hello!

I’m Olivia, I’m some twenty-something woman who likes to document and romanticize my life because I feel and think deeply(often to a fault). I hope to find others who enjoy documenting and maybe hope to inspire others to do so too. I love little moments, small details, things that invoke emotion and inspiration. I practice witchcraft, and that’s what my pages originally became popular for. I enjoy reading, and while I was a non-fiction lover for years, I’m beginning to enjoy fiction a lot again.
